vrd:talk rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:TalkToableThing ;
         rdfs:comment """Property 'talk' has two different and equally frequent meanings/usages:
1) 'talk' as in 'talk on', eg (person, talk, phone)
2) 'talk' as in 'talk to', eg (person, talk, person)

These two visual relationship instances are the only ones present in the annotations of the VRD training set (original and customised versions)."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#tallerThan
vrd:tallerThan rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                        owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:comment "This property is a 'comparative' spatial relation. It's the only such property used in the VRD image annotations. It means simply that the 'subject' is taller than the 'object'."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#touch
vrd:touch rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:comment """Property 'touch' is used
a) as a verb, where the subject is most often 'person'
b) as in 'on'
c) as in spatial relation 'next to', where the subject is usually NOT 'person'

The mixture of meanings/usage makes it awkward to describe it with particular defining characteristics.

Property 'touch' (much like 'hold' and 'lean on' and 'has') implies close proximity, which means we could choose to model 'touch' as a subproperty of spatial relation properties like 'next to' and 'beside'. But we choose not to do this.

If 'touch' were used as a pure spatial relation (case (c)), we could model it as being 'symmetric'.  But its usage as a verb (case (a)) works against such symmetry. If A is in the act of touching B, it doesn't imply that B is in the act of touching A.  Or we could argue that if (A, touch, B) and the 'verb' usage applies in the forward direction then, at the very least, the spatial relation usage will still apply in the backward direction, meaning we could model 'touch' as being symmetric.  But we choose not to do this."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#under
vrd:under rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:below ;
          rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "We treat property 'under' as a more specialised version of property 'below', ie as a subproperty of 'below'. We take the view that if (A, under, B), not only is A lower than B (relative to some notional vertical axis), it is also *directly below* B. That is, if A and B were projected onto the same 2D plane that's orthogonal to the notional vertical axis, they would occupy a common point in that 2D plane."@en .


