###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#Street
vrd:Street rdf:type owl:Class ;
           rdfs:subClassOf vrd:MixedGroundSurface ;
           rdfs:comment """Within the VRD image annotations, the object class label 'street' has dramatically diverse  meanings/usages. These meanings/usages span the following types of things:
* city street (roadway and sidewalk)
* city sidewalk (excluding roadway)
* road (dirt road, country lane)
* floor (in a room or building)
* ground (dirt)
* tennis court surfaces
* snow (eg snow covered ground at a ski resort)
* airfield (at an airport)
* airport concourse floor surface
* grass

Basically, the object class 'street' seems to have been used as a catch-all for 'the ground' or 'the surface of the earth', whatever its form. It's a reference to the surface upon which the other earth-bound objects in the image are all ultimately sitting; a kind of opposite to 'the sky'.

The number of images whose annotations refer to 'street' is so large (775 in the original training set), and the diversity of meanings/usages so wide, that cleaning the situation to bring precision to the matter was too daunting a task to undertake.   Some customisations have been applied, however.  For example, many (perhaps most) instances where 'street' was used to refer to a city sidewalk have been customised away in favour of a bounding box that includes both the roadway and sidewalk as the object labelled 'street'.

A consequence of this wide diversity of meaning/usage is that our ontology class 'Street' was awkward to place within the ontology class hierarchy. For example, instances of 'street' include both engineered things (like city streets and tennis courts) and natural things (like grass, dirt and snow).  Needing a home for class 'Street' is what initially led to the creation of the category 'MixedEnvironmentThing' in the ontology class hierarchy.

Be aware that the VRD image annotations also recognise an object class of 'road'.  Upon inspection, the examples of 'road' were indistinguishable from those of 'street'.  If anything, the examples of 'road' referred more consistently to 'city street' objects than do the examples of 'street'.  The examples of 'road' and 'street' were clearly drawn from the same distribution and there was no basis for distinguishing between them, even for a human.  The decision was taken to merge all instances of object class 'road' into object class 'street'.  So there is no class 'Road' in this ontology."""@en .


