vrd:adjacentTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               owl:equivalentProperty vrd:beside ,
                                      vrd:nextTo ;
               rdf:type owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#against
vrd:against rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:inFrontOf ;
            rdfs:range vrd:Sky ;
            rdfs:comment "The meaning/usage of property 'against' has been standardised to be consistent with the spatial relation notion of 'set against', where, if (A, against, B), then A is in the foreground with B as its background.  For example, (mountain, against, sky) or (tower, against, sky).  The 'object' of such triples is always 'sky'.  This meaning/usage also enables the relationship between 'against' and 'in the front of' to be declared."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#at
vrd:at rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
       rdfs:domain [ rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     owl:unionOf ( vrd:Chair
                                   vrd:Person
                                 )
                   ] .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#attachedTo
vrd:attachedTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                        owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#behind
vrd:behind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                    owl:TransitiveProperty ;
           rdfs:comment "This property is a pure spatial relation.  We regard it as a 'directional' spatial relation because it expresses a sense of relative position with respect to an axis of a 3D frame of reference, in this case one of the two axes forming the 2D plane orthogonal to a notional vertical axis."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#below
vrd:below rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                   owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "This property is a pure spatial relation.  We regard it as a 'directional' spatial relation because it expresses a sense of relative position with respect to an axis of a 3D frame of reference, in this case the vertical axis."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#beneath
