           rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#lyingOn
vrd:lyingOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#near
vrd:near rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                  owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#nextTo
vrd:nextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                    owl:SymmetricProperty ;
           rdfs:comment """Property 'nextTo' is used consistently as a pure spatial relation. Like all pure spatial relations, anything can be said to be 'nextTo' anything else, so the domain and range of this property cannot be restricted in any meaningful way.

It is conceivable that one might opt to model property 'nextTo' as being a more specialised version of a property such as 'near', using a subPropertyOf relationship.  If (A, nextTo, B), then it can be argued that (A, near, B), but not necessarily the other way round. But in this version of VRD-World we have chosen NOT to model such a subPropertyOf relation.  Others may well take a different view on such matters."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#on
vrd:on rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       rdfs:comment """Property 'on' has two very different primary meanings/usages:

1) 'on' as in the spatial relation 'on the top of'; for example, (hat, on, person) or (cup, on, table)

2) 'on' as in an inverse of the verb 'wear'; for example, (shirt, on, person), (glasses, on, person)

Due to its usage as a spatial relation, its domain and range cannot be restricted because, in general, anything can be  located 'on' anything else. And due to the dual meanings/usages, it's not feasible to describe other defining characteristics either."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTheLeftOf
vrd:onTheLeftOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
                owl:inverseOf vrd:onTheRightOf ;
                rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTheRightOf
vrd:onTheRightOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                          owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTopOf
vrd:onTopOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ,
                               vrd:over .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#outsideOf
vrd:outsideOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
              rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:by ;
              rdfs:range vrd:OutsideOfCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#over
vrd:over rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:above ;
         owl:inverseOf vrd:under ;
         rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
         rdfs:comment "We treat property 'over' as a specialisation of (ie a subproperty of) property 'above', which is used as a pure spacial relation. If (A, over, B), then A is not only above B (as in 'higher than' B relative to some notional vertical axis), it is also 'directly above' B.  So 'over' is a specialisation because it means 'directly above'. That is, if (A, over, B) and we were to project objects A and B onto a 2D plane that's orthogonal to the notional vertical axis, A and B would occupy a common point in the 2D plane."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#parkBehind
vrd:parkBehind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
