vrd:standUnder rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:under ;
               rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#talk
vrd:talk rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:TalkToableThing ;
         rdfs:comment """Property 'talk' has two different and equally frequent meanings/usages:
1) 'talk' as in 'talk on', eg (person, talk, phone)
2) 'talk' as in 'talk to', eg (person, talk, person)

These two visual relationship instances are the only ones present in the annotations of the VRD training set (original and customised versions)."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#tallerThan
vrd:tallerThan rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                        owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:comment "This property is a 'comparative' spatial relation. It's the only such property used in the VRD image annotations. It means simply that the 'subject' is taller than the 'object'."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#touch
vrd:touch rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:comment """Property 'touch' is used
a) as a verb, where the subject is most often 'person'
b) as in 'on'
c) as in spatial relation 'next to', where the subject is usually NOT 'person'

The mixture of meanings/usage makes it awkward to describe it with particular defining characteristics.

Property 'touch' (much like 'hold' and 'lean on' and 'has') implies close proximity, which means we could choose to model 'touch' as a subproperty of spatial relation properties like 'next to' and 'beside'. But we choose not to do this.

If 'touch' were used as a pure spatial relation (case (c)), we could model it as being 'symmetric'.  But its usage as a verb (case (a)) works against such symmetry. If A is in the act of touching B, it doesn't imply that B is in the act of touching A.  Or we could argue that if (A, touch, B) and the 'verb' usage applies in the forward direction then, at the very least, the spatial relation usage will still apply in the backward direction, meaning we could model 'touch' as being symmetric.  But we choose not to do this."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#under
vrd:under rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:below ;
          rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "We treat property 'under' as a more specialised version of property 'below', ie as a subproperty of 'below'. We take the view that if (A, under, B), not only is A lower than B (relative to some notional vertical axis), it is also *directly below* B. That is, if A and B were projected onto the same 2D plane that's orthogonal to the notional vertical axis, they would occupy a common point in that 2D plane."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#use
vrd:use rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
        rdfs:range vrd:Device .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walk
vrd:walk rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:Dog ;
         rdfs:comment "This property is highly specific and used in (multiple instances of) only 1 distinct visual relationship: (person, walk, dog)."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walkBeside
vrd:walkBeside rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               owl:equivalentProperty vrd:walkNextTo ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walkNextTo
vrd:walkNextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walkOn
vrd:walkOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal ;
           rdfs:range vrd:WalkableSurface .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walkTo
vrd:walkTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal ;
           rdfs:label "walk towards"@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#watch
vrd:watch rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal ;
          rdfs:comment """Property 'watch' has a consistent meaning/usage as a verb: to watch.

We could model it explicitly as a subproperty of 'face', but we choose instead to do this implicitly via the equivalence with property 'look at', which is explicitly declared to be a subproperty of 'face'.  This strategy of relying on the equivalence with 'look at' to establish an implicit subproperty relationship with 'face' is designed to avoid the inference of unnecessary duplicate (:x, :face, :y) triples which would otherwise occur whenever an (:x, :watch, :y) or (:x, :lookAt, :y) triple is asserted, since either such assertion would lead to 2 duplicate (:x, :face, :y) triples being inferred.  We can think of this strategy as a rudimentary ontology design pattern.  We apply this same pattern elsewhere in the vrd_dh_custom ontology as well. For example, properties 'beneath' and 'under' are declared to be equivalent, but only 'under' is modelled explicitly as being a subproperty of 'below'."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#wear
vrd:wear rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:has ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:WearCapableThing ;
         rdfs:range vrd:WearableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#with
vrd:with rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                  owl:SymmetricProperty ;
         rdfs:comment """This property has multiple meanings/usages in the VRD image annotations.
It's used:
1) in the sense of 'near' and 'by', eg (person, with, person)
2) in the sense of 'wear', eg (person, with, watch), (person, with, glasses)
3) in the sense of 'carry' or 'has', eg (person, with, bag), (building, with, clock)
4) in the sense of support or host or 'contain', eg (cabinet, with, drinking glass), (bench, with, person), (vase, with, plant)

The multiple meanings/usages limits the defining characteristics we can use to describe this property.  For example, we can't make it a subproperty of, say, 'has' because then a triple such as (helmet, with, person) would lead to the inference of triple (helmet, has, person), which is unnatural language and unwanted.  Similarly, we can't make it a subproperty of 'next to'. If (helmet, with, person) and the person is actually wearing the helmet, then inferring triple (helmet, next to, person) would be unnatural language and unwanted.  The spatial relation meaning/usage, in (1), means we can't restrict the domain and range in a meaningful way."""@en .


