                                                            owl:versionIRI <http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world/1.0> ;
                                                            dc:description """This ontology, VRD-World,  is a well-aligned companion to the NeSy4VRD dataset.

The NeSy4VRD dataset consists of the images of the VRD dataset and their associated NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations. The NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations are a highly customised and quality-improved version of the original VRD visual relationship annotations. 

This ontology, VRD-World, describes the domain of the NeSy4VRD dataset as reflected in the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations.  An annotated visual relationship is a 5-tuple, (subj_bbox, subj_class, predicate, obj_bbox, obj_class), where subj_bbox and subj_class are the bounding box and class of a 'subject' object, and obj_bbox and obj_class are the bounding box and class of an 'object' object. The predicate describes some relation between this ordered pair of objects. So an annotated visual relationship can, for simplicity, be thought of as being a 3-tuple: (subject, predicate, object).  Each instance of an annotated visual relationship is associated with one unique VRD image and describes a particular relation between a particular ordered pair of objects within that image. A bounding box is specified using 4 integers representing two opposing corners of the box: xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax. An example visual relationship for a particular image, described in 3-tuple form, is: (person, ride, horse).

The VRD-World ontology is designed to capture all of the information contained in the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations. This includes representations of 1) the VRD images themselves, 2) all of the objects annotated for each image (including their assigned classes and their bounding boxes with their particular bounding box specifications), and 3) all of the predicates describing relations between particular objects.  Each object class referenced within the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations has a corresponding class within the VRD-World class hierarchy; each predicate referenced within the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations has a corresponding VRD-World object property.

One can load the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations in their entirety  into a knowledge graph governed by the VRD-World ontology, extract them again, and reconstitute the NeSy4VRD visual relationship annotations completely, in their native format, without loss of information."""@en ;
                                                            dc:title "vrd_world"@en ;
                                                            dcterms:contributor "David Herron" ;
                                                            dcterms:license "Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 (CC BY 4.0)"^^xsd:string ;
                                                            dcterms:provenance "v1.0"@en ;
                                                            rdfs:label "vrd_world"@en ;
                                                            owl:versionInfo "1.0"^^xsd:string .

#################################################################
#    Annotation properties
#################################################################

###  http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/description
dc:description rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .


###  http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title
dc:title rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .


###  http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor
dcterms:contributor rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .


###  http://purl.org/dc/terms/license
dcterms:license rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .


###  http://purl.org/dc/terms/provenance
dcterms:provenance rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .


#################################################################
#    Object Properties
#################################################################

###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#above
vrd:above rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          owl:inverseOf vrd:below ;
          rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "This property is a pure spatial relation.  We regard it as a 'directional' spatial relation because it expresses a sense of relative position with respect to an axis of a 3D frame of reference, in this case the vertical axis."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#acrossFrom
vrd:acrossFrom rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:face ,
                                  vrd:inFrontOf ;
               rdf:type owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#adjacentTo
vrd:adjacentTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               owl:equivalentProperty vrd:beside ,
                                      vrd:nextTo ;
               rdf:type owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#against
vrd:against rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:inFrontOf ;
            rdfs:range vrd:Sky ;
            rdfs:comment "The meaning/usage of property 'against' has been standardised to be consistent with the spatial relation notion of 'set against', where, if (A, against, B), then A is in the foreground with B as its background.  For example, (mountain, against, sky) or (tower, against, sky).  The 'object' of such triples is always 'sky'.  This meaning/usage also enables the relationship between 'against' and 'in the front of' to be declared."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#at
vrd:at rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
       rdfs:domain [ rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     owl:unionOf ( vrd:Chair
                                   vrd:Person
                                 )
                   ] .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#attachedTo
vrd:attachedTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                        owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#behind
vrd:behind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                    owl:TransitiveProperty ;
           rdfs:comment "This property is a pure spatial relation.  We regard it as a 'directional' spatial relation because it expresses a sense of relative position with respect to an axis of a 3D frame of reference, in this case one of the two axes forming the 2D plane orthogonal to a notional vertical axis."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#below
vrd:below rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                   owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "This property is a pure spatial relation.  We regard it as a 'directional' spatial relation because it expresses a sense of relative position with respect to an axis of a 3D frame of reference, in this case the vertical axis."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#beneath
vrd:beneath rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            owl:equivalentProperty vrd:under ;
            owl:inverseOf vrd:over ;
            rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#beside
vrd:beside rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           owl:equivalentProperty vrd:nextTo ;
           rdf:type owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#by
vrd:by rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       owl:equivalentProperty vrd:near ;
       rdf:type owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#carry
vrd:carry rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:has ;
          rdfs:domain vrd:CarryCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#contain
vrd:contain rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            owl:inverseOf vrd:inside ;
            rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#cover
vrd:cover rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:domain [ rdf:type owl:Class ;
                        owl:unionOf ( vrd:Sky
                                      vrd:Tree
                                      vrd:Trees
                                      vrd:Umbrella
                                    )
                      ] .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#drive
vrd:drive rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:use ;
          rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
          rdfs:range vrd:DrivableMotorisedVehicle .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#driveOn
vrd:driveOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:RoadMotorisedVehicle ;
            rdfs:range vrd:Street .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#eat
vrd:eat rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:has ;
        rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal ;
        rdfs:range vrd:EatableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#face
vrd:face rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:comment """Property 'face' has a consistent meaning/usage with the VRD image annotations. It's used in the sense of 'face in the direction of'. So it's less of a verb and more like a spatial relation, except that it's expressing an attitude or orientation of the 'subject' relative to the 'object' rather than their relative positions in space.

It has similarities with properties 'watch' and 'look at', as well as with 'across from'. But 'face' feels the most general of these properties, so the others are modelled as subproperties of 'face'.

This property has little in the way of defining characteristics."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#feed
vrd:feed rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:Mammal ;
         rdfs:comment "Property 'feed' is used solely in the sense of 'feeds something to': (A, feed, B) means (A, feeds something to, B).  The something is unknown."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#fly
vrd:fly rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:playWith ;
        rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
        rdfs:range vrd:Kite .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#flyIn
vrd:flyIn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:in ;
          rdfs:domain vrd:FlyableThing ;
          rdfs:range vrd:Sky .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#follow
vrd:follow rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:behind ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:MotionCapableThing ;
           rdfs:range vrd:MotionCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#has
vrd:has rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:comment """Property 'has' is one of the most common and most general purpose predicates in the visual relationship annotations of the VRD dataset. In the original VRD training set annotations it's used with 66 distinct 'subject' object classes and 81 distinct 'object' object classes.

It has diverse meanings/usages:
a) 'has' as a sort of inverse of a notional 'part of' relation, eg (tower, has, clock)
b) 'has' as in 'wear', eg (person, has, shirt)
c) 'has' as in hosts or supports, eg (table, has, plate)
d) 'has' as in 'hold' or 'with' or 'carry', eg (person, has, bag)

Predicate 'has' is used with so many VRD images we simply have to accept this diversity of meaning. A key consequence of this diversity, however, is that it's not feasible to restrict the domain/range of this property in any meaningful way, or to declare other defining characteristics (such as equivalence, inverses, symmetry, etc.).  There is, in effect, virtually nothing we can say about this general purpose property to describe or constrain its use."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#hasBbox
vrd:hasBbox rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                     owl:FunctionalProperty ,
                     owl:InverseFunctionalProperty ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:VRDWorldThing ;
            rdfs:range vrd:Bbox ;
            rdfs:comment "Property 'hasBbox' relates an individual VRD material world thing to its bounding box specification that describes where the individual object is located within its VRD image." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#hasObject
vrd:hasObject rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
              owl:inverseOf vrd:sourceImage ;
              rdf:type owl:InverseFunctionalProperty ;
              rdfs:domain vrd:Image ;
              rdfs:range vrd:VRDWorldThing ;
              rdfs:comment "A property to associate an image with the an individual object (VRD material world thing) identified (detected) within the image." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#hit
vrd:hit rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:playWith ;
        rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
        rdfs:range vrd:Ball .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#hold
vrd:hold rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:has ,
                            vrd:touch ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:HoldCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#in
vrd:in rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       rdfs:comment """Property 'in' has three very different primary meanings/usages:

1) spatial relation, as in 'inside': eg (dog, in, basket)

2) verb, as in 'wear': eg (person, in, shirt)

3) 'surrounded by' or 'amongst' or 'in the midst of': eg (giraffe, in, grass) or (person, in, street)

Due to its usage as a spatial relation, its domain and range cannot be restricted because, in general, anything can be  located 'on' anything else. And due to the multiple diverse meanings, it's not feasible to describe other defining characteristics either."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#inFrontOf
vrd:inFrontOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                       owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#inside
vrd:inside rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:in ;
           rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#kick
vrd:kick rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:playWith ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:Ball .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#leanOn
vrd:leanOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:touch ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:LeanableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#lookAt
vrd:lookAt rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           owl:equivalentProperty vrd:watch ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:face ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#lyingOn
vrd:lyingOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#near
vrd:near rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                  owl:SymmetricProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#nextTo
vrd:nextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                    owl:SymmetricProperty ;
           rdfs:comment """Property 'nextTo' is used consistently as a pure spatial relation. Like all pure spatial relations, anything can be said to be 'nextTo' anything else, so the domain and range of this property cannot be restricted in any meaningful way.

It is conceivable that one might opt to model property 'nextTo' as being a more specialised version of a property such as 'near', using a subPropertyOf relationship.  If (A, nextTo, B), then it can be argued that (A, near, B), but not necessarily the other way round. But in this version of VRD-World we have chosen NOT to model such a subPropertyOf relation.  Others may well take a different view on such matters."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#on
vrd:on rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
       rdfs:comment """Property 'on' has two very different primary meanings/usages:

1) 'on' as in the spatial relation 'on the top of'; for example, (hat, on, person) or (cup, on, table)

2) 'on' as in an inverse of the verb 'wear'; for example, (shirt, on, person), (glasses, on, person)

Due to its usage as a spatial relation, its domain and range cannot be restricted because, in general, anything can be  located 'on' anything else. And due to the dual meanings/usages, it's not feasible to describe other defining characteristics either."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTheLeftOf
vrd:onTheLeftOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
                owl:inverseOf vrd:onTheRightOf ;
                rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTheRightOf
vrd:onTheRightOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                          owl:TransitiveProperty .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#onTopOf
vrd:onTopOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ,
                               vrd:over .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#outsideOf
vrd:outsideOf rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
              rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:by ;
              rdfs:range vrd:OutsideOfCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#over
vrd:over rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:above ;
         owl:inverseOf vrd:under ;
         rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
         rdfs:comment "We treat property 'over' as a specialisation of (ie a subproperty of) property 'above', which is used as a pure spacial relation. If (A, over, B), then A is not only above B (as in 'higher than' B relative to some notional vertical axis), it is also 'directly above' B.  So 'over' is a specialisation because it means 'directly above'. That is, if (A, over, B) and we were to project objects A and B onto a 2D plane that's orthogonal to the notional vertical axis, A and B would occupy a common point in the 2D plane."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#parkBehind
vrd:parkBehind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:behind ;
               rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:MotorisedVehicle .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#parkNextTo
vrd:parkNextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:MotorisedVehicle .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#parkOn
vrd:parkOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:ParkableMotorisedVehicle ;
           rdfs:range vrd:ParkableSurface .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#playWith
vrd:playWith rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
             rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:use ;
             rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
             rdfs:range vrd:PlayWithCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#pull
vrd:pull rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:inFrontOf ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:PullCapableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#restOn
vrd:restOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
           rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
           rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#ride
vrd:ride rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:RidableThing .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sitBehind
vrd:sitBehind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
              rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:behind ;
              rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
              rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sitNextTo
vrd:sitNextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
              rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
              rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sitOn
vrd:sitOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
          rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sitUnder
vrd:sitUnder rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
             rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:under ;
             rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
             rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#skateOn
vrd:skateOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
            rdfs:range vrd:SkateboardingRelatedThing ;
            rdfs:comment "Property 'skateOn' has a consistent meaning/usage relating to skateboarding."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sleepNextTo
vrd:sleepNextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
                rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
                rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sleepOn
vrd:sleepOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#sourceImage
vrd:sourceImage rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                         owl:FunctionalProperty ;
                rdfs:domain vrd:VRDWorldThing ;
                rdfs:range vrd:Image ;
                rdfs:comment "A property to associate a VRD material world thing (an individual object) with the VRD image from whose visual relationship annotations the thing originated." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#standBehind
vrd:standBehind rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
                rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:behind ;
                rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
                rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#standNextTo
vrd:standNextTo rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
                rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:nextTo ;
                rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#standOn
vrd:standOn rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
            rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:on ;
            rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#standUnder
vrd:standUnder rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:under ;
               rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:domain vrd:Mammal .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#talk
vrd:talk rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:TalkToableThing ;
         rdfs:comment """Property 'talk' has two different and equally frequent meanings/usages:
1) 'talk' as in 'talk on', eg (person, talk, phone)
2) 'talk' as in 'talk to', eg (person, talk, person)

These two visual relationship instances are the only ones present in the annotations of the VRD training set (original and customised versions)."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#tallerThan
vrd:tallerThan rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ,
                        owl:TransitiveProperty ;
               rdfs:comment "This property is a 'comparative' spatial relation. It's the only such property used in the VRD image annotations. It means simply that the 'subject' is taller than the 'object'."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#touch
vrd:touch rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:comment """Property 'touch' is used
a) as a verb, where the subject is most often 'person'
b) as in 'on'
c) as in spatial relation 'next to', where the subject is usually NOT 'person'

The mixture of meanings/usage makes it awkward to describe it with particular defining characteristics.

Property 'touch' (much like 'hold' and 'lean on' and 'has') implies close proximity, which means we could choose to model 'touch' as a subproperty of spatial relation properties like 'next to' and 'beside'. But we choose not to do this.

If 'touch' were used as a pure spatial relation (case (c)), we could model it as being 'symmetric'.  But its usage as a verb (case (a)) works against such symmetry. If A is in the act of touching B, it doesn't imply that B is in the act of touching A.  Or we could argue that if (A, touch, B) and the 'verb' usage applies in the forward direction then, at the very least, the spatial relation usage will still apply in the backward direction, meaning we could model 'touch' as being symmetric.  But we choose not to do this."""@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#under
vrd:under rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
          rdfs:subPropertyOf vrd:below ;
          rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty ;
          rdfs:comment "We treat property 'under' as a more specialised version of property 'below', ie as a subproperty of 'below'. We take the view that if (A, under, B), not only is A lower than B (relative to some notional vertical axis), it is also *directly below* B. That is, if A and B were projected onto the same 2D plane that's orthogonal to the notional vertical axis, they would occupy a common point in that 2D plane."@en .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#use
vrd:use rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
        rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
        rdfs:range vrd:Device .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/nesy4vrd/ontologies/vrd_world#walk
vrd:walk rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
         rdfs:domain vrd:Person ;
         rdfs:range vrd:Dog ;
         rdfs:comment "This property is highly specific and used in (multiple instances of) only 1 distinct visual relationship: (person, walk, dog)."@en .


